00:01:41.840 --> 00:02:23.199
 
 

00:02:23.199 --> 00:02:26.090
Those are the equations.
 

00:02:26.090 --> 00:02:29.397
The first one tells you that if
you draw any surface and

00:02:29.397 --> 00:02:31.894
integrate
B over that surface,

00:02:31.894 --> 00:02:35.705
namely, you're counting the net
number of lines coming out,

00:02:35.705 --> 00:02:37.348
you're going to get 0.
 

00:02:37.348 --> 00:02:40.496
That's because lines begin and
end with charges and there are

00:02:40.496 --> 00:02:41.650
no magnetic charges.
 

00:02:41.650 --> 00:02:43.747
If you look at any magnetic
field problem,

00:02:43.747 --> 00:02:46.050
the lines don't have a
beginning or an end.

00:02:46.050 --> 00:02:48.199
They end on themselves.
 

00:02:48.199 --> 00:02:51.791
So if you put any surface
there, whatever goes in has to

00:02:51.791 --> 00:02:52.508
come out.
 

00:02:52.508 --> 00:02:55.020
That's the statement of no
magnetic charges.

00:02:55.020 --> 00:02:57.193
This one says,
yes, there are things that

00:02:57.193 --> 00:02:59.910
manufacture electric field lines
called charges.

00:02:59.910 --> 00:03:01.718
They make them and they eat
them.

00:03:01.718 --> 00:03:05.936
Depending on how many got in
the volume, the net will decide

00:03:05.936 --> 00:03:08.080
the flux out of that volume.
 

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:11.269
This one, without that,
used to say electric field is a

00:03:11.269 --> 00:03:12.508
conservative field.
 

00:03:12.508 --> 00:03:14.878
It defines a potential and so
on.

00:03:14.878 --> 00:03:17.543
But then we found in the time
dependent problem,

00:03:17.543 --> 00:03:20.943
E⋅dl,
we said rate of change of the

00:03:20.943 --> 00:03:22.020
magnetic field.
 

00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:25.740
So changing magnetic field
sustains an electric field.

00:03:25.740 --> 00:03:29.229
And this one says a changing
electric field can produce a

00:03:29.229 --> 00:03:30.288
magnetic field.
 

00:03:30.288 --> 00:03:32.801
In addition,
a current can also produce a

00:03:32.801 --> 00:03:33.870
magnetic field.
 

00:03:33.870 --> 00:03:39.090
This is what we have to begin
with.

00:03:39.090 --> 00:03:43.628
Now I'm going to eventually
focus on free space.

00:03:43.628 --> 00:03:49.949
Free space means we're nowhere
near charges and currents.

00:03:49.949 --> 00:03:52.400
And the equations become more
symmetric.

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:55.244
This has got no surface
integral, that has got no

00:03:55.244 --> 00:03:56.370
surface integral.
 

00:03:56.370 --> 00:03:59.730
The line integral of this guy
is essentially the rate of

00:03:59.730 --> 00:04:01.258
change of flux of that.
 

00:04:01.258 --> 00:04:08.555
And the line integral of that
guy is - the rate of change of

00:04:08.555 --> 00:04:10.408
flux of this.
 

00:04:10.408 --> 00:04:14.431
If I'm going to get a wave
equation, the triumphant moment

00:04:14.431 --> 00:04:18.949
is when I do this and do that
and out comes the wave equation.

00:04:18.949 --> 00:04:23.254
But if at that moment you have
not seen the wave equation,

00:04:23.254 --> 00:04:26.050
you're not going to get the
thrill.

00:04:26.050 --> 00:04:29.177
So I have to know,
how many people remember the

00:04:29.177 --> 00:04:32.579
wave equation from the first
part of the course?

00:04:32.579 --> 00:04:36.430
Okay, so I think I have to
remind you of what that is.

00:04:36.430 --> 00:04:39.177
It's a bit like explaining a
joke, but still,

00:04:39.177 --> 00:04:42.235
I have to do that,
because otherwise we won't have

00:04:42.235 --> 00:04:43.860
that climactic moment.
 

00:04:43.860 --> 00:04:47.389
So let me tell you one example
of a wave equation.

00:04:47.389 --> 00:04:49.029
People have seen them before.
 

00:04:49.029 --> 00:04:50.980
Here is the simplest example.
 

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:54.995
You take a string,
you tie it between two fixed

00:04:54.995 --> 00:04:58.399
points and it has a tension
T.

00:04:58.399 --> 00:05:02.269
Tension is the force with which
the two ends are being pulled.

00:05:02.269 --> 00:05:06.853
Then you distort it in some
form and you release it,

00:05:06.853 --> 00:05:09.278
and you see what happens.
 

00:05:09.278 --> 00:05:16.478
Now let's measure x as
the distance from the left end

00:05:16.478 --> 00:05:22.699
and y as the height at
that time t.

00:05:22.699 --> 00:05:27.432
The wave equation tells you an
equation governing the behavior

00:05:27.432 --> 00:05:28.519
of y.
 

00:05:28.519 --> 00:05:31.778
It tells you how y
varies.

00:05:31.778 --> 00:05:35.086
Now if you want to do that,
you may think you have to

00:05:35.086 --> 00:05:37.250
invent new stuff,
but you don't.

00:05:37.250 --> 00:05:40.009
Everything comes from Newton's
laws.

00:05:40.009 --> 00:05:43.786
That's to me the amazing part,
that you have these equations,

00:05:43.786 --> 00:05:46.620
then of course the Lorentz
force equations.

00:05:46.620 --> 00:05:49.367
Then you've got Newton's laws
and that's all we have up to

00:05:49.367 --> 00:05:50.670
this point in the course.
 

00:05:50.670 --> 00:05:53.942
So there should be no need to
invoke anything beyond Newton's

00:05:53.942 --> 00:05:56.290
laws to find out the fate of
this string.

00:05:56.290 --> 00:05:59.000
And namely, we are going to
apply F = ma,

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.519
but not to the whole string at
one time,

00:06:01.519 --> 00:06:04.036
because a is the
acceleration and whose

00:06:04.036 --> 00:06:06.050
acceleration are we talking
about?

00:06:06.050 --> 00:06:07.889
Piece of string here,
piece of string there?

00:06:07.889 --> 00:06:10.490
It can all be moving at
different rates.

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:14.360
So you pick a tiny portion,
which I'm going to blow up for

00:06:14.360 --> 00:06:15.379
your benefit.
 

00:06:15.379 --> 00:06:17.620
That's a piece of string.
 

00:06:17.620 --> 00:06:21.411
Its interval,
it lies under region of length

00:06:21.411 --> 00:06:22.470
dx.
 

00:06:22.470 --> 00:06:25.910
In other words,
you take a dx here and

00:06:25.910 --> 00:06:27.629
look at that string.
 

00:06:27.629 --> 00:06:32.572
It is being pulled like that
with a tension T and it's

00:06:32.572 --> 00:06:37.019
being pulled like this with a
tension T here.

00:06:37.019 --> 00:06:40.860
That's the meaning of tension,
pulled at both ends.

00:06:40.860 --> 00:06:43.648
If this was a perfectly
straight segment,

00:06:43.648 --> 00:06:47.553
there'll be no net force on it,
because these forces will

00:06:47.553 --> 00:06:48.319
cancel.
 

00:06:48.319 --> 00:06:52.821
But if it's slightly curved,
then this line and that line

00:06:52.821 --> 00:06:57.242
are not quite in the same
direction and the forces don't

00:06:57.242 --> 00:06:58.769
have to cancel.
 

00:06:58.769 --> 00:07:03.028
So let's take that force and
write its vertical part.

00:07:03.028 --> 00:07:06.860
If this angle is
θ,

00:07:06.860 --> 00:07:12.297
T times
sinθ is the force

00:07:12.297 --> 00:07:13.410
here.
 

00:07:13.410 --> 00:07:18.365
-T times (because
T is pointing the

00:07:18.365 --> 00:07:21.872
opposite way)--
let me call this

00:07:21.872 --> 00:07:28.333
θ_1 and
θ_2 is

00:07:28.333 --> 00:07:31.290
the angle you have here.
 

00:07:31.290 --> 00:07:32.209
Do you understand?
 

00:07:32.209 --> 00:07:36.476
The vertical force is restoring
the strength to where it was is

00:07:36.476 --> 00:07:37.990
what I'm focused on.
 

00:07:37.990 --> 00:07:40.622
So you resolve that force into
a vertical part,

00:07:40.622 --> 00:07:43.199
up and this one has the
vertical part down.

00:07:43.199 --> 00:07:45.523
Now if θ_1 =
θ_2 they

00:07:45.523 --> 00:07:46.980
cancel and that's what I just
said.

00:07:46.980 --> 00:07:48.565
But θ_1
and θ_2

00:07:48.565 --> 00:07:50.730
are generally not equal,
because if I go to the top of

00:07:50.730 --> 00:07:52.273
the string,
for example,

00:07:52.273 --> 00:07:56.110
this end is pulling this way,
that end is pulling that way.

00:07:56.110 --> 00:07:58.420
There's a net force down.
 

00:07:58.420 --> 00:08:02.533
So you have a net force because
this angle or the tangent to the

00:08:02.533 --> 00:08:04.819
string is changing with
position.

00:08:04.819 --> 00:08:06.930
That's why they don't cancel.
 

00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:10.910
Now the approximation I'm going
to make is that theta is small,

00:08:10.910 --> 00:08:14.250
measured in radians,
and I remind you that

00:08:14.250 --> 00:08:19.055
sinθ is essentially
θ - very small

00:08:19.055 --> 00:08:20.360
corrections.
 

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:24.975
And cosine θ is 1
− θ^(2)/2

00:08:24.975 --> 00:08:26.089
corrections.
 

00:08:26.089 --> 00:08:29.682
And tanθ,
which is the ratio of these

00:08:29.682 --> 00:08:32.908
guys, is θ other
corrections.

00:08:32.908 --> 00:08:35.173
For a very small
θ,

00:08:35.173 --> 00:08:37.730
you forget that,
you forget that.

00:08:37.730 --> 00:08:42.529
You keep things of order theta
in every equation.

00:08:42.529 --> 00:08:44.500
So for small angles,
cosine is just 1,

00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:46.740
and sinθ is
θ.

00:08:46.740 --> 00:08:48.970
If you do that,
and sinθ and

00:08:48.970 --> 00:08:52.590
tanθ being equal,
I can write it as

00:08:52.590 --> 00:08:59.190
tanθ_1 -
tanθ_2.

00:08:59.190 --> 00:09:01.660
But that's in the
approximation,

00:09:01.660 --> 00:09:05.090
where tan and sine are all
roughly equal.

00:09:05.090 --> 00:09:11.552
That is really T times
dy/dx at the point x

00:09:11.552 --> 00:09:15.825
dx −
dy/dx at the point

00:09:15.825 --> 00:09:17.250
x.
 

00:09:17.250 --> 00:09:17.620
Are you with me?
 

00:09:17.620 --> 00:09:20.259
dy/dx from calculus,
you remember,

00:09:20.259 --> 00:09:21.250
is the slope.
 

00:09:21.250 --> 00:09:23.590
It's a partial derivative.
 

00:09:23.590 --> 00:09:25.799
Why is it a partial derivative
now?

00:09:25.799 --> 00:09:28.950
Can you tell me?
 

00:09:28.950 --> 00:09:29.798
Yes?
 

00:09:29.798 --> 00:09:30.519
Student:  It's all
dependent on time.

00:09:30.519 --> 00:09:33.091
Prof: It can depend on
time and I'm doing F = ma

00:09:33.091 --> 00:09:34.399
at one instant in time.
 

00:09:34.399 --> 00:09:36.726
So I don't want to take this
guy's slope now and that guy's

00:09:36.726 --> 00:09:37.610
slope an hour later.
 

00:09:37.610 --> 00:09:42.309
I want them at the same time,
at a fixed time.

00:09:42.309 --> 00:09:46.490
Now what do I do with this?
 

00:09:46.490 --> 00:09:52.298
Have I taught you guys how to
handle a difference like this?

00:09:52.298 --> 00:09:56.129
There's one legacy I want to
leave behind is what to do when

00:09:56.129 --> 00:09:58.789
confronted with a difference
like this.

00:09:58.789 --> 00:10:03.490
You have any idea what to do?
 

00:10:03.490 --> 00:10:04.320
Pardon me?
 

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:07.350
Student:  Multiply by
one.

00:10:07.350 --> 00:10:10.659
Prof: Multiply by one.
 

00:10:10.659 --> 00:10:13.009
Then what do you do with that?
 

00:10:13.009 --> 00:10:15.985
I'm asking you to evaluate the
difference between this guy at

00:10:15.985 --> 00:10:18.120
x dx - the same thing at
x.

00:10:18.120 --> 00:10:25.695
What is it equal to
approximately for small

00:10:25.695 --> 00:10:27.860
dx?
 

00:10:27.860 --> 00:10:29.470
Let me ask you another question.
 

00:10:29.470 --> 00:10:34.078
Suppose I have f of x
dx and I subtract from it

00:10:34.078 --> 00:10:37.460
f of x,
what is it equal to?

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:48.428
Student: 
&gt;

00:10:48.428 --> 00:10:51.424
Prof: If I divide by
Δx and take the

00:10:51.424 --> 00:10:53.158
limit, it becomes a derivative.
 

00:10:53.158 --> 00:10:55.345
If I don't divide by
Δx,

00:10:55.345 --> 00:10:58.450
this is then df/dx
times Δx.

00:10:58.450 --> 00:11:02.485
There may be other corrections,
but when Δx goes

00:11:02.485 --> 00:11:05.090
to 0, you may make that
approximation.

00:11:05.090 --> 00:11:06.950
That is the meaning of the rate
of change.

00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:08.773
If I tell you,
here's a function and that's

00:11:08.773 --> 00:11:10.988
the same function somewhere to
the right, what's the

00:11:10.988 --> 00:11:11.639
difference?
 

00:11:11.639 --> 00:11:13.777
That's what the role of the
derivative is,

00:11:13.777 --> 00:11:15.548
to tell you how much it
changes.

00:11:15.548 --> 00:11:17.690
This slope changes from here to
there,

00:11:17.690 --> 00:11:20.767
therefore it's a derivative of
something which is already a

00:11:20.767 --> 00:11:24.214
derivative,
so it's d^(2)y/dx^(2)

00:11:24.214 --> 00:11:26.629
times Δx.
 

00:11:26.629 --> 00:11:29.455
In other words,
the f I'm using here is itself

00:11:29.455 --> 00:11:32.467
dy/dx and the
df/dx is then the

00:11:32.467 --> 00:11:33.850
second derivative.
 

00:11:33.850 --> 00:11:36.649
So that's the force.
 

00:11:36.649 --> 00:11:43.190
Now that force we must equate
to ma.

00:11:43.190 --> 00:11:44.240
That's the easy part.
 

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:48.330
What is the mass of this
section, this portion of string?

00:11:48.330 --> 00:11:54.221
If the mass per unit length is
μ, that's the mass of that

00:11:54.221 --> 00:11:55.220
section.
 

00:11:55.220 --> 00:11:57.308
Then what's the acceleration.
 

00:11:57.308 --> 00:12:00.610
Acceleration is the rate at
which y is going up and down.

00:12:00.610 --> 00:12:05.519
That is d^(2)y/dt^(2).
 

00:12:05.519 --> 00:12:14.916
Canceling the Δx,
we get this wave equation which

00:12:14.916 --> 00:12:23.095
says d^(2)y/dx^(2) -
μ over T

00:12:23.095 --> 00:12:29.662
d^(2)y/dt^(2) is 0,
and that's the origin of the

00:12:29.662 --> 00:12:30.288
wave equation.
 

00:12:30.288 --> 00:12:34.530
Any time you get something like
this, you call it the wave

00:12:34.530 --> 00:12:35.350
equation.
 

00:12:35.350 --> 00:12:42.436
I'm going to write this as
d^(2)y/dx^(2) - 1 over

00:12:42.436 --> 00:12:47.590
v^(2) d^(2)y/dt^(2 )= 0
where v is

00:12:47.590 --> 00:12:51.070
√(T/μ).
 

00:12:51.070 --> 00:12:54.482
I use the symbol v,
because this will turn out to

00:12:54.482 --> 00:12:57.090
be the velocity of waves on that
string.

00:12:57.090 --> 00:13:00.162
Namely, if you pluck the string
and make a little bump here,

00:13:00.162 --> 00:13:03.234
let it go, the bump will move
and v is going to be the speed

00:13:03.234 --> 00:13:04.379
at which it moves.
 

00:13:04.379 --> 00:13:08.443
The speed of waves is
determined by the tension and

00:13:08.443 --> 00:13:10.639
the mass per unit length.
 

00:13:10.639 --> 00:13:14.495
Now I want to show you that
this really is the velocity of

00:13:14.495 --> 00:13:15.240
the wave.
 

00:13:15.240 --> 00:13:17.009
How do we know that's the
velocity?

00:13:17.009 --> 00:13:19.917
It's got dimensions of
velocity, but maybe it's not the

00:13:19.917 --> 00:13:21.210
velocity of this wave.
 

00:13:21.210 --> 00:13:23.080
Maybe it's something else.
 

00:13:23.080 --> 00:13:26.690
I want to show you that
v stands for the velocity

00:13:26.690 --> 00:13:28.658
of the waves in this medium.
 

00:13:28.658 --> 00:13:33.039
The way you do that is you ask
yourself, what is the nature of

00:13:33.039 --> 00:13:35.408
the solutions to this equation?
 

00:13:35.408 --> 00:13:41.196
If y(x,t) satisfied the
equation, what can you say about

00:13:41.196 --> 00:13:43.250
its functional form?
 

00:13:43.250 --> 00:13:46.178
What functions do you think
will play a role?

00:13:46.178 --> 00:13:53.384
Does anybody have any idea what
kind of functions may play a

00:13:53.384 --> 00:13:54.240
role?
 

00:13:54.240 --> 00:13:55.379
Student:  Sine function?
 

00:13:55.379 --> 00:13:57.029
Prof: Sines maybe.
 

00:13:57.029 --> 00:13:59.255
With single oscillators,
when you have something

00:13:59.255 --> 00:14:01.481
something is d/dt
squared, you had cosine

00:14:01.481 --> 00:14:02.428
ωt.
 

00:14:02.428 --> 00:14:04.960
Whatever you can do for t
you can do for x.

00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:06.558
You can have a cosine in
x.

00:14:06.558 --> 00:14:09.293
So you might think it is all
sines and cosines and

00:14:09.293 --> 00:14:10.129
exponentials.
 

00:14:10.129 --> 00:14:14.424
All that is true,
but it turns out the range of

00:14:14.424 --> 00:14:17.879
solutions is much bigger than
that.

00:14:17.879 --> 00:14:20.702
I'm going to write down for you
the most generation solution to

00:14:20.702 --> 00:14:22.933
the wave equation,
namely what's the constraint it

00:14:22.933 --> 00:14:24.210
imposes on the function?
 

00:14:24.210 --> 00:14:31.907
The answer is this - y
can be any function you want of

00:14:31.907 --> 00:14:33.960
x - vt.
 

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:37.538
I don't care what function it
is.

00:14:37.538 --> 00:14:42.774
So if I call z as a
single variable x - vt,

00:14:42.774 --> 00:14:47.726
y can be a function of
this single combination,

00:14:47.726 --> 00:14:49.408
x - vt.
 

00:14:49.408 --> 00:14:51.221
In other words,
y can depend on x

00:14:51.221 --> 00:14:53.269
and y can depend on
t. If it depends on

00:14:53.269 --> 00:14:55.120
x and t in an
arbitrary way,

00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:57.320
of course it won't satisfy this
equation.

00:14:57.320 --> 00:15:00.952
But I'm telling you that if it
depends on x and t

00:15:00.952 --> 00:15:03.532
only through this combination,
x - vt,

00:15:03.532 --> 00:15:05.759
it will satisfy the wave
equation.

00:15:05.759 --> 00:15:07.379
In other words,
here's the function.

00:15:07.379 --> 00:15:11.299
You don't even have to
think, x - vt squared

00:15:11.299 --> 00:15:14.750
over some number
x_0^(2).

00:15:14.750 --> 00:15:17.649
That's a completely good
solution to the wave equation.

00:15:17.649 --> 00:15:21.958
I guarantee if you took this,
it would satisfy the wave

00:15:21.958 --> 00:15:26.028
equation, because it's a
function only of x - vt.

00:15:26.028 --> 00:15:30.186
A function that's not a good
function is y = e^(

00:15:30.186 --> 00:15:33.178
−x2) −
v^(2)t^(2).

00:15:33.178 --> 00:15:35.558
That's not a function of x -
vt.

00:15:35.558 --> 00:15:42.340
That won't satisfy the wave
equation.

00:15:42.340 --> 00:15:46.860
So why is that true is what I
want to show you.

00:15:46.860 --> 00:15:51.710
Let us take dy/dx.
 

00:15:51.710 --> 00:15:58.351
Remember, y depends only
on this combination z,

00:15:58.351 --> 00:16:04.330
therefore it equals df/dz
times dz/dx.

00:16:04.330 --> 00:16:09.318
But z is x - vt,
dz/dx is 1,

00:16:09.318 --> 00:16:12.230
so it's just df/dz.
 

00:16:12.230 --> 00:16:14.879
Now let me rush through this
and do it one more time.

00:16:14.879 --> 00:16:16.570
Everything will go the same way.
 

00:16:16.570 --> 00:16:21.250
You will get this.
 

00:16:21.250 --> 00:16:27.690
But how about dy/dt?
 

00:16:27.690 --> 00:16:33.107
If you want dy/dt,
again you take df/dz

00:16:33.107 --> 00:16:35.928
times dz/dt.
 

00:16:35.928 --> 00:16:40.647
But that gives you--this should
be written as a

00:16:40.647 --> 00:16:46.389
partial--dz/dt is
df/dz times -v.

00:16:46.389 --> 00:16:47.889
Can you see that?
 

00:16:47.889 --> 00:16:50.221
By the chain rule,
you take any function you have,

00:16:50.221 --> 00:16:52.460
first differentiate with
respect to z.

00:16:52.460 --> 00:16:54.908
Then differentiate z
with respect to x and

00:16:54.908 --> 00:16:56.110
with respect to t.
 

00:16:56.110 --> 00:16:57.629
If you do an x
derivative, you get 1.

00:16:57.629 --> 00:16:59.562
If you do a t
derivative,

00:16:59.562 --> 00:17:00.808
you get -v.
 

00:17:00.808 --> 00:17:03.732
Now if I do it twice--again,
I don't want to spend too much

00:17:03.732 --> 00:17:05.951
time--if I do it twice,
I'm going to skip the

00:17:05.951 --> 00:17:07.058
intermediate step.
 

00:17:07.058 --> 00:17:12.058
I'll get a -v and a
−v^(2).

00:17:12.058 --> 00:17:15.880
It follows then that if I took
1/v^(2) times that,

00:17:15.880 --> 00:17:17.450
can you see that now?
 

00:17:17.450 --> 00:17:27.458
1/v^(2) d^(2)y/dt^(2) is
the same as v^(2)y

00:17:27.458 --> 00:17:29.960
dx^(2).
 

00:17:29.960 --> 00:17:32.160
Therefore to satisfy the wave
equation,

00:17:32.160 --> 00:17:35.724
it can be any function at all,
as long as it depends on

00:17:35.724 --> 00:17:39.490
x and t in the
combination x - vt.

00:17:39.490 --> 00:17:40.828
That is just a mathematical
fact.

00:17:40.828 --> 00:17:43.506
You just have to do the chain
rule, you will find that it's

00:17:43.506 --> 00:17:43.828
true.
 

00:17:43.828 --> 00:17:46.612
But more importantly,
I want you to understand what

00:17:46.612 --> 00:17:48.950
it tells you about the wave
propagation.

00:17:48.950 --> 00:17:51.608
Let me pick x_0
= 1 for convenience.

00:17:51.608 --> 00:17:55.890
Let me plot this guy at time
t = 0.

00:17:55.890 --> 00:18:00.619
This solution looks like
e to the -x

00:18:00.619 --> 00:18:06.220
squared, which is a function
like that, at t = 0.

00:18:06.220 --> 00:18:10.160
What does it look like at t
= 1 second?

00:18:10.160 --> 00:18:11.519
Think about it.
 

00:18:11.519 --> 00:18:15.493
t = 1 second looks like
e to the -x - v

00:18:15.493 --> 00:18:16.940
whole squared.
 

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:22.390
That means it's the same bump,
shifted by an amount v.

00:18:22.390 --> 00:18:25.796
See this function x - v
squared behaves with respect to

00:18:25.796 --> 00:18:28.700
x = v the same as the
original function around

00:18:28.700 --> 00:18:29.650
x = 0.
 

00:18:29.650 --> 00:18:32.761
Whatever happens to this guy
here happens to that guy at

00:18:32.761 --> 00:18:34.630
distance v to the right.
 

00:18:34.630 --> 00:18:37.492
You can see that if you wait
t seconds,

00:18:37.492 --> 00:18:40.230
it would have moved a distance
vt.

00:18:40.230 --> 00:18:43.730
That's why you understand that
vt,

00:18:43.730 --> 00:18:45.900
v is the velocity of
propagation,

00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:49.053
because what this is telling
you is that if you start the

00:18:49.053 --> 00:18:52.150
system out with some
configuration at time t,

00:18:52.150 --> 00:18:55.070
t = 0,
later on the function looks

00:18:55.070 --> 00:18:58.722
like the same function
translated to the right at a

00:18:58.722 --> 00:19:00.328
velocity v.
 

00:19:00.328 --> 00:19:04.124
That means its profile,
whatever profile you have,

00:19:04.124 --> 00:19:06.368
is just moved to the right.
 

00:19:06.368 --> 00:19:16.241
Now can you think of another
family of solutions besides this

00:19:16.241 --> 00:19:17.230
one?
 

00:19:17.230 --> 00:19:21.720
Why should the wave move to the
right?

00:19:21.720 --> 00:19:22.608
Yes?
 

00:19:22.608 --> 00:19:25.098
Student:  It's x
vt.

00:19:25.098 --> 00:19:27.348
Prof: Do you understand
that if it was x vt,

00:19:27.348 --> 00:19:30.252
you go through this derivation,
you'd get a v^(2)

00:19:30.252 --> 00:19:32.758
instead of a
−v^(2) and that

00:19:32.758 --> 00:19:33.838
doesn't matter.
 

00:19:33.838 --> 00:19:37.126
So the answer is,
the most general solution to

00:19:37.126 --> 00:19:40.853
the wave equation is any
function you like of x -

00:19:40.853 --> 00:19:44.358
vt any function you like of
x vt.

00:19:44.358 --> 00:19:46.220
This will describe waves going
to the right;

00:19:46.220 --> 00:19:48.713
that will describe waves going
to the left, and you can

00:19:48.713 --> 00:19:49.500
superpose them.
 

00:19:49.500 --> 00:19:53.509
Because it's a linear equation,
you can add solutions.

00:19:53.509 --> 00:19:55.848
This is what I want you to know
about the wave equation.

00:19:55.848 --> 00:20:01.108
This is one example of how the
wave equation comes and what the

00:20:01.108 --> 00:20:03.568
meaning of the symbol v is.
 

00:20:03.568 --> 00:20:08.480
Now let me go to the old
Maxwell equations.

00:20:08.480 --> 00:20:11.910
Now I want to do them and ask
myself.

00:20:11.910 --> 00:20:16.474
I'm going to write down a
solution and I'm going to see if

00:20:16.474 --> 00:20:19.680
it obeys these four Maxwell
equations.

00:20:19.680 --> 00:20:23.429
If I write down a solution for
the electric field and the

00:20:23.429 --> 00:20:26.241
magnetic field,
they have to obey all those

00:20:26.241 --> 00:20:28.720
conditions, those four
equations.

00:20:28.720 --> 00:20:32.356
That means, let's take first
the case of working in a vacuum,

00:20:32.356 --> 00:20:35.509
when there is no current,
when there is no charge.

00:20:35.509 --> 00:20:37.240
So you want a surface integral
of

00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:43.751
E on any surface to be 0
and the surface integral of

00:20:43.751 --> 00:20:47.568
B on any surface to be 0.
 

00:20:47.568 --> 00:20:50.819
Look at the surface integral
first.

00:20:50.819 --> 00:20:51.338
Do you understand?
 

00:20:51.338 --> 00:20:53.470
This was never going to be
non-zero.

00:20:53.470 --> 00:20:56.150
This will be non-zero near
matter but we are far from any

00:20:56.150 --> 00:20:58.829
charges, so there is nothing to
enclose in the volume.

00:20:58.829 --> 00:21:01.079
There are no charges there.
 

00:21:01.079 --> 00:21:02.170
Look at those equations.
 

00:21:02.170 --> 00:21:05.224
I give you a function and I
say, "Tell me if it

00:21:05.224 --> 00:21:07.321
satisfies Maxwell's
equations,"

00:21:07.321 --> 00:21:08.940
what do you have to do?
 

00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:14.618
Operationally,
what is it that you have to do?

00:21:14.618 --> 00:21:24.559
Any ideas on what you must do
at this point to test?

00:21:24.559 --> 00:21:26.078
Any ideas?
 

00:21:26.078 --> 00:21:33.269
What do you have to see of a
potential solution?

00:21:33.269 --> 00:21:34.509
Come on, this is not the New
York subway.

00:21:34.509 --> 00:21:36.630
You can make eye contact.
 

00:21:36.630 --> 00:21:38.250
What is this?
 

00:21:38.250 --> 00:21:41.269
You have no idea what you may
have to do?

00:21:41.269 --> 00:21:45.372
What if I give you a function
and say, "See if it

00:21:45.372 --> 00:21:47.926
satisfies the wave
equation,"

00:21:47.926 --> 00:21:49.940
what will you do then?
 

00:21:49.940 --> 00:21:51.329
Take the function and then what?
 

00:21:51.329 --> 00:21:52.170
Yes?
 

00:21:52.170 --> 00:21:53.500
Student:  Differentiate
it and see--

00:21:53.500 --> 00:21:54.140
Prof: Yes!
 

00:21:54.140 --> 00:21:56.165
Take x derivative,
y derivative and all

00:21:56.165 --> 00:21:57.180
that, second derivative.
 

00:21:57.180 --> 00:21:59.229
If it vanishes,
you'll say it satisfies it,

00:21:59.229 --> 00:21:59.618
right?
 

00:21:59.618 --> 00:22:01.430
That's what it means to satisfy
it.

00:22:01.430 --> 00:22:05.053
If I give you fields
E and B that

00:22:05.053 --> 00:22:10.010
depends on space and time and I
want you to verify if it

00:22:10.010 --> 00:22:13.435
satisfies this,
what do you have to do,

00:22:13.435 --> 00:22:15.598
is what I'm asking?
 

00:22:15.598 --> 00:22:17.700
Student:  Come up with a
situation?

00:22:17.700 --> 00:22:18.875
Prof: No,
it must be true in every

00:22:18.875 --> 00:22:19.230
situation.
 

00:22:19.230 --> 00:22:22.074
In other words,
what's the surface on which

00:22:22.074 --> 00:22:23.700
this integral is done?
 

00:22:23.700 --> 00:22:26.849
On what surface do we do the
integral?

00:22:26.849 --> 00:22:27.509
Pardon me?
 

00:22:27.509 --> 00:22:28.569
Student:  Closed.
 

00:22:28.569 --> 00:22:29.588
Prof: Closed.
 

00:22:29.588 --> 00:22:31.210
But beyond closed,
anything else?

00:22:31.210 --> 00:22:31.980
Where is it located?
 

00:22:31.980 --> 00:22:36.480
How big is it?
 

00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:37.078
Pardon me?
 

00:22:37.078 --> 00:22:41.019
Student: 
&gt;

00:22:41.019 --> 00:22:42.259
Prof: I didn't hear that.
 

00:22:42.259 --> 00:22:43.210
Student:  It's
everywhere.

00:22:43.210 --> 00:22:46.041
Prof: It could be
anywhere and it could have any

00:22:46.041 --> 00:22:46.410
size.
 

00:22:46.410 --> 00:22:47.920
It could have any shape.
 

00:22:47.920 --> 00:22:52.029
And it must be true for all
those surfaces.

00:22:52.029 --> 00:22:54.387
So if I just give you a field,
E (x,y,z and

00:22:54.387 --> 00:22:56.170
t), it's a lot of work,
right?

00:22:56.170 --> 00:22:58.150
Draw all possible surfaces.
 

00:22:58.150 --> 00:23:01.471
On them, you can take the
surface, divide it into patches,

00:23:01.471 --> 00:23:04.853
do the surface integral patch
by patch, and you better keep

00:23:04.853 --> 00:23:05.670
getting 0.
 

00:23:05.670 --> 00:23:08.980
When you're done with that,
then you take the magnetic

00:23:08.980 --> 00:23:09.480
field.
 

00:23:09.480 --> 00:23:12.712
Then the other two Maxwells
tell you, take a loop,

00:23:12.712 --> 00:23:16.868
any loop, go round that and do
the line integral of B.

00:23:16.868 --> 00:23:19.534
That should be the flux
crossing it, the electric flux

00:23:19.534 --> 00:23:20.490
or magnetic flux.
 

00:23:20.490 --> 00:23:23.660
And it should be done for every
loop and for every surface.

00:23:23.660 --> 00:23:26.348
You realize that looks
impossible.

00:23:26.348 --> 00:23:30.910
But there is a quicker way to
verify all of these equations,

00:23:30.910 --> 00:23:37.976
and the quick way is the
following - if these equations

00:23:37.976 --> 00:23:42.951
are true for a tiny loop,
in this case,

00:23:42.951 --> 00:23:48.599
true for a tiny volume or a
tiny surface enclosing a tiny

00:23:48.599 --> 00:23:54.298
volume,
then it's true for big ones.

00:23:54.298 --> 00:23:59.459
And likewise,
if true for a tiny loop,

00:23:59.459 --> 00:24:04.480
it is true for any arbitrary
loop.

00:24:04.480 --> 00:24:06.846
In other words,
if I can show that at any

00:24:06.846 --> 00:24:10.561
arbitrary point,
if I pick an infinitesimal loop

00:24:10.561 --> 00:24:14.244
or infinitesimal surface,
and these guys satisfy these

00:24:14.244 --> 00:24:16.180
equations on an infinitesimal
thing,

00:24:16.180 --> 00:24:19.519
it's going to satisfy it on a
macroscopic thing.

00:24:19.519 --> 00:24:21.529
That's what we want to
understand.

00:24:21.529 --> 00:24:24.200
How does that come about?
 

00:24:24.200 --> 00:24:29.166
It comes about due to a very
beautiful way in which we define

00:24:29.166 --> 00:24:31.319
the sum of two surfaces.
 

00:24:31.319 --> 00:24:35.769
So here is a surface.
 

00:24:35.769 --> 00:24:37.855
I'm going to take everything to
be a cube, but it's not

00:24:37.855 --> 00:24:38.319
important.
 

00:24:38.319 --> 00:24:40.078
Here's a surface.
 

00:24:40.078 --> 00:24:41.779
Let's call it
S_1.

00:24:41.779 --> 00:24:43.680
And it's got its outward normal.
 

00:24:43.680 --> 00:24:47.157
That's the definition of
surface integral is you draw the

00:24:47.157 --> 00:24:49.457
normals pointing outwards and
you take

00:24:49.457 --> 00:24:52.873
E⋅dA
on every face of the cube

00:24:52.873 --> 00:24:53.930
and add it.
 

00:24:53.930 --> 00:24:58.936
The area vector is defined to
be outward pointing normal to

00:24:58.936 --> 00:25:00.059
every face.
 

00:25:00.059 --> 00:25:01.890
So you take the little cube.
 

00:25:01.890 --> 00:25:05.396
E may be pointing this
way there or that way there,

00:25:05.396 --> 00:25:09.089
but you take the dot product of
the area and you add them.

00:25:09.089 --> 00:25:16.059
Then I take a second cube here.
 

00:25:16.059 --> 00:25:21.940
Let's see.
 

00:25:21.940 --> 00:25:24.259
It's got its own outward normal.
 

00:25:24.259 --> 00:25:27.920
This is surface 2.
 

00:25:27.920 --> 00:25:33.289
Now imagine gluing this guy to
this guy, so it looks like this.

00:25:33.289 --> 00:25:40.460
You glue this common face.
 

00:25:40.460 --> 00:25:46.327
Bring that surface over and
glue them with that face common

00:25:46.327 --> 00:25:47.338
to both.
 

00:25:47.338 --> 00:25:51.586
Then I claim that the surface
integral on this one the surface

00:25:51.586 --> 00:25:55.693
integral on that one is the
surface integral on the union of

00:25:55.693 --> 00:25:56.529
the two.
 

00:25:56.529 --> 00:26:02.355
In other words,
let's see, take one cube,

00:26:02.355 --> 00:26:09.345
take another cube,
and that surface integral will

00:26:09.345 --> 00:26:14.880
be the same as on a longer
object.

00:26:14.880 --> 00:26:18.980
I don't know what this is
called, something over that.

00:26:18.980 --> 00:26:24.440
The two cubes used to be
sharing this.

00:26:24.440 --> 00:26:25.578
Do you understand why?
 

00:26:25.578 --> 00:26:28.882
Let's understand why the
integral on this guy,

00:26:28.882 --> 00:26:32.404
which is, if you want,
two cubes joined to form a

00:26:32.404 --> 00:26:34.019
rectangular solid.
 

00:26:34.019 --> 00:26:38.252
That surface integral is the
sum of these two surface

00:26:38.252 --> 00:26:39.230
integrals.
 

00:26:39.230 --> 00:26:43.440
Think for a minute about why
that is true.

00:26:43.440 --> 00:26:46.256
If you compare them,
piece by piece,

00:26:46.256 --> 00:26:48.670
this face matches that face.
 

00:26:48.670 --> 00:26:50.380
This face matches that half.
 

00:26:50.380 --> 00:26:51.940
This one matches that half.
 

00:26:51.940 --> 00:26:54.671
But something is missing in
this that's present here,

00:26:54.671 --> 00:26:55.460
do you agree?
 

00:26:55.460 --> 00:26:59.230
What is it we don't have?
 

00:26:59.230 --> 00:27:00.069
What's missing in the equal
union?

00:27:00.069 --> 00:27:00.578
Yes?
 

00:27:00.578 --> 00:27:01.868
Student:  Two sides
equal _________.

00:27:01.868 --> 00:27:05.317
Prof: The two common
faces are missing in the big

00:27:05.317 --> 00:27:07.450
surface, but it does not matter.
 

00:27:07.450 --> 00:27:10.420
The two common faces do not
matter because when you do the

00:27:10.420 --> 00:27:13.490
surface on the first one,
the outward normal will point

00:27:13.490 --> 00:27:15.099
out of that,
whereas if you do it on the

00:27:15.099 --> 00:27:17.151
second one,
the outward normal will point

00:27:17.151 --> 00:27:18.288
into the other one.
 

00:27:18.288 --> 00:27:22.492
When you glue them together,
the common face is opposite

00:27:22.492 --> 00:27:23.640
orientations.
 

00:27:23.640 --> 00:27:27.598
Consequently,
the surface integral on the big

00:27:27.598 --> 00:27:33.269
solid is equal to the sum of the
surface in integrals in the two

00:27:33.269 --> 00:27:34.799
small solids.
 

00:27:34.799 --> 00:27:35.450
Do you follow that?
 

00:27:35.450 --> 00:27:36.390
That's the way it works.
 

00:27:36.390 --> 00:27:40.161
Then you can go on adding more
and more pieces to this,

00:27:40.161 --> 00:27:43.653
right, and you can build like
Legos and arbitrarily

00:27:43.653 --> 00:27:45.118
complicated blob.
 

00:27:45.118 --> 00:27:47.432
Remember, these are all very,
very tiny volumes,

00:27:47.432 --> 00:27:49.990
so you can build them up to
look like a big thing.

00:27:49.990 --> 00:27:50.930
It may look like a pyramid.
 

00:27:50.930 --> 00:27:53.910
If you look very closely,
you'll have the steps like in a

00:27:53.910 --> 00:27:56.199
real pyramid,
but the steps here can be made

00:27:56.199 --> 00:27:57.368
arbitrarily small.
 

00:27:57.368 --> 00:28:00.721
Therefore if the surface
integral was 0 on every little

00:28:00.721 --> 00:28:03.019
piece that made up the big
object,

00:28:03.019 --> 00:28:04.720
then it's going to be 0 on the
big object,

00:28:04.720 --> 00:28:08.589
because the integral on the big
object is the integral of the

00:28:08.589 --> 00:28:11.298
tiny pieces that make up the big
object.

00:28:11.298 --> 00:28:14.983
This is a very profound idea,
because the big object has

00:28:14.983 --> 00:28:17.528
fewer surfaces than the small
ones,

00:28:17.528 --> 00:28:21.558
because when you cut it,
you create two new surfaces,

00:28:21.558 --> 00:28:24.029
but they don't contribute
between the two of them,

00:28:24.029 --> 00:28:26.838
because they cancel.
 

00:28:26.838 --> 00:28:29.979
And in particular,
if the surface integral had not

00:28:29.979 --> 00:28:32.953
been 0,
but because of matter it was

00:28:32.953 --> 00:28:37.402
equal to charge inside volume 1,
and this right hand side of

00:28:37.402 --> 00:28:39.910
this one was the charge inside
volume 2,

00:28:39.910 --> 00:28:43.249
you can see that the surface
integral on the bigger surface

00:28:43.249 --> 00:28:45.380
will be the sum of the two
charges.

00:28:45.380 --> 00:28:47.890
So anything you're trying to
prove about surface integrals,

00:28:47.890 --> 00:28:50.068
even if the right hand side is
not 0,

00:28:50.068 --> 00:28:52.984
if it is true in a tiny cube,
true in a union of two cubes

00:28:52.984 --> 00:28:55.849
and then in a union of any
number of these tiny guys,

00:28:55.849 --> 00:28:59.079
therefore on any surface.
 

00:28:59.079 --> 00:29:00.460
That's the thing to remember.
 

00:29:00.460 --> 00:29:04.150
What we will do then is not to
take arbitrary surfaces,

00:29:04.150 --> 00:29:07.244
but infinitesimal surfaces and
we'll prove for them that the

00:29:07.244 --> 00:29:10.497
Maxwell equations are satisfied
for the solution that I come up

00:29:10.497 --> 00:29:10.970
with.
 

00:29:10.970 --> 00:29:14.932
Then you're guaranteed that it
will work for an arbitrary

00:29:14.932 --> 00:29:15.640
surface.
 

00:29:15.640 --> 00:29:18.858
When you do line
integrals--this is for surface

00:29:18.858 --> 00:29:21.730
integral--line integral is even
easier.

00:29:21.730 --> 00:29:26.665
Suppose I'm taking the line
integral of some function around

00:29:26.665 --> 00:29:27.670
this loop.
 

00:29:27.670 --> 00:29:29.150
This is loop
